I would suggest avoid using a while loop (that keeps on running for nothing).

Instead, you can use a recursive function call.

1. Creating the buttons array:

```Java
bt1=findViewById(R.id.button);
bt2=findViewById(R.id.button2);
bt3=findViewById(R.id.button3);
bt4=findViewById(R.id.button4);

Button[]all={bt1,bt2,bt3,bt4};
ArrayList&lt;Button&gt; arr_new = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(all));
```

2. Shuffle the array
```Java
Collections.shuffle(arr_new);
```

3. Now that you have a randomly ordered array of buttons, you can simply take the first one (it was randomly picked to be the first...), wait for a click, remove it from the list and again.. take the first one, click, remove..

4. Let&#39;s define the recursive function. It calls itself until no more buttons left in the shuffled array:

```Java
void untilAllSelected(ArrayList&lt;Button&gt; buttons) {
    
    // Check if not more buttons - this means we clicked all of them..
    if (buttons.isEmpty()) {
        return;
    }
    
    // Set the clicked button color
    buttons.get(0).setBackgroundColor(Color.RED);
    // Set a click listener on the first button
    buttons.get(0).setOnClickListener(v -&gt; {
        // When clicked - remove the listener to avoid feature clicks
        v.setOnClickListener(null);
        
        // Remove the clicked button from the list
        buttons.remove(0);
        
        // Recursively call the function with the buttons list (which is now 1 button shorter)
        untilAllSelected(buttons);
    });
}
```

5. Last thing, call the recursive function. Here&#39;s the complete code:


```Java

